Architected multi-invoice model reconciling deposits with Xero timing constraints
Yes, this is very solvable — and actually if we get the model right here, the deposit flow falls out for free and fixes the post-payment edit problem we just discussed. Let me walk you through it.

The mental model shift

Up to now we've been treating an invoice as a snapshot of the whole order. That's why supersession felt necessary — if the order changes, the snapshot is stale, so we throw it away and make a new one. But it also means the model can only ever have one "real" invoice at a time, which is exactly why deposits don't fit.

The cleaner model: an invoice is a claim for a portion of the order's value, not a snapshot of the whole thing. An order can have several invoices live at once. The order's payment state is just the sum of those invoices and the payments against them.

Once you make that shift, deposits, balance invoices, supplementary invoices, and the post-payment-edit case all work the same way.

Add an Invoice Type field

type: enum  (Deposit / Balance / Full / Supplementary)
amount: decimal  (the portion of the order this invoice covers)
Default is Full for the standard flow. Deposit and Balance are used together for the deposit flow. Supplementary handles upward edits after payment.

The existing rule still holds: the sum of all non-Superseded invoices on an order equals the order total. That's the invariant — enforce it everywhere.

How the deposit flow looks

Customer commits to a £1,000 order with delivery in 3 months.
Order is created in Confirmed status. Stock is reserved (this is the actual functional reason for taking a deposit — it locks the stock).
Staff clicks "Split into Deposit + Balance" on the order. A modal asks for the deposit amount (£300). System generates:
Invoice 1: Deposit, £300, Unpaid
Invoice 2: Balance, £700, Unpaid
Customer pays Invoice 1 (Stripe link, bank transfer, whatever). Invoice 1 → Paid. Order is "Partially Paid (£300 of £1,000)".
Three months pass. Stock is reserved the entire time.
Order moves through Ready to Pick → Staged → Packed → Dispatched as normal.
Customer pays Invoice 2 before/at collection. Invoice 2 → Paid. Order is "Paid".
Order completes 24 hours after dispatch.
The standard (non-deposit) flow is identical, just with one invoice

Order created → Invoice 1 (Full, £1,000, Unpaid) auto-generated → pre-dispatch edits supersede this single invoice (same as today) → customer pays → done. Nothing changes for the 95% case.

The post-payment edit case (from the previous question) becomes trivial

Customer paid Invoice 1 for £400. Order needs to go up to £450. System generates Invoice 2 (Supplementary, £50, Unpaid). Both invoices coexist; the order is now "Partially Paid (£400 of £450)". No supersession of a paid invoice ever happens. Clean.

If the order needs to go down, that's a credit note against the paid invoice (PRD-3.3), same as before.

Now — the Xero timing question. This needs honest examination.

Your instinct is "keep the Xero ping at the very end." That instinct came from a real pain point: Ariane re-doing Xero work when orders change. But that pain only happens when an unpaid invoice gets edited. A paid deposit invoice will never be edited — it's a completed transaction. So the original reason to delay Xero posting doesn't apply to paid invoices.

I'd recommend the rule become: invoices post to Xero when paid, OR 24h after dispatch — whichever comes first.

Deposit gets paid in May → that invoice posts to Xero in May.
Balance gets paid at collection in August → that invoice posts to Xero in August (or 24h after dispatch if unpaid on credit terms).
A standard credit-terms order: invoice posts to Xero 24h after dispatch, paid or not — exactly as today.
This preserves Ariane's pain relief (no edits to Xero-posted invoices) while letting the deposit money show up in Xero when it actually arrives, which is what her bank reconciliation needs anyway.

One thing worth verifying with Ariane / your accountant before locking this in

UK VAT rules generally treat a deposit as a tax point — meaning VAT is due at the point the deposit is received, not at final delivery. If that's right, then sitting on a paid deposit for 3 months without it appearing in Xero would be an actual HMRC issue, not just a workflow inconvenience. The "post on payment" rule above handles this correctly, but it's worth Ariane confirming explicitly so the dev team knows it's a hard requirement, not just a nice-to-have.

Three changes to the PRD

Delete the "Deposits — MacPlants does not take deposits" paragraph. It's no longer true and contradicts this flow. Replace with the deposit flow described above.
Add type and amount fields to the Invoice schema. Add the invariant: sum of non-Superseded invoice amounts on an order equals the order total.
Update the Xero posting rule: "An invoice posts to Xero when it is marked Paid, OR 24 hours after order dispatch/collection — whichever comes first. Once posted to Xero, an invoice is read-only."

